-- AMR, Camac Energy, Delcath, Leap Wireless, MetroPCS: U.S. Equity Movers
-- B y   K a t i a   P o r z e c a n s k i
-- 2011-12-30T21:15:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-29/amr-harleysville-group-patterson-uti-energy-sears-u-s-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in U.S. trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 4 p.m. in  New York .  AMR Corp. (AMR)   fell 32 percent to 35 cents for the
biggest retreat in the Russell 1000 Index. NYSE Euronext said
shares of the parent of  American Airlines  will be removed from
the New York Stock Exchange before trading begins on Jan. 5,
following the  Fort Worth , Texas-based company’s bankruptcy
filing on Nov. 29.  Camac Energy Inc. (CAK)   rallied 15 percent, the most
since Nov. 2, to $1.01. The oil and gas company agreed to buy
three exploration licenses in western  Africa  and said its
partner, an Eni SpA (ENI IM) unit, will sell its 40 percent
stake in a Nigerian project to Allied Energy Plc.  Delcath Systems Inc. (DCTH)   declined 12 percent, the
most in the Russell 2000 Index, to $3.05. The developer of an
experimental system for giving anti-cancer drugs said it may
sell shares worth as much as $39.8 million through Cowen & Co.
LLC. Additional stock may dilute the value of existing shares.  MetroPCS Communications Inc. (PCS)   climbed 5.3 percent,
the biggest gain on the  S&P 500 , to $8.68. The pay-as-you-go
wireless carrier rose a second day after JPMorgan Chase & Co.
said it is a possible takeover target for AT&T Inc. or  T-Mobile
USA  after the larger companies’ $39 billion merger plan
collapsed.  Leap Wireless International Inc. (LEAP)  , also
named by JPMorgan as a target, jumped 9.4 percent to $9.29, for
a two-day surge of 14 percent.  MoSys Inc. (MOSY)   surged 41 percent, the most since
February 2004, to $4.20. The company whose designs boost memory-
chip capacity and trim power use agreed to sell 73 patents to a
Tessera Technologies Inc. (TSRA US) unit for $35 million.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 